@node Main "Appendix 4: Date Strings..."
@toc "FinalCalc:guide/main.guide/Main"
@font topaz.font 8
A Date String is a text string that describes a date.  It is converted by the
Date String Parser (as described below) into a FinalCalc date number.  This
is used in several places in FinalCalc:

- Editing a Date cell.  (e.g. set a cell type to Date, and enter a date
  string into it)

- Date string gadget in requesters.

- DATEVALUE() math function  (e.g.  DATEVALUE("12 feb 1994") )


@{b}@{u}Date String Parser:@{ub}@{uu}

The Date String Parser takes a string that resembles a date and returns a date
number.  

The simplest format for a date is composed of the following:

  - a number between 1 and 31  (day)
  - a three letter (or more) month name
  - a year number (between 1900 and 2999, or 50 and 99)

For example:  12 feb 94

If you don't specify the year (e.g. "12 feb"), it defaults to the current year.

You can also specify the date without a day number (e.g. "feb 95"), it which case
it defaults to the first day of the month.


The parser also accepts a flexible description of the date, such as:

    friday
    next monday
    last monday
    second last monday
    today
    first monday in jan 94
    last monday in feb
    first tuesday next month
    last tuesday this month
    third friday last month
    first day next year
    

The parser accepts the following keywords:


    @{u}Keyword         @{uu}    @{u}Action/effect                                       @{uu} 
    number: 1-31        Set day number

    JAN        \\        Set month
    FEB        |
    MAR        |
    APR        |
    MAY        |
    JUN        |
    JUL        |
    AUG        |
    SEP        |
    OCT        |
    NOV        |
    DEC        /

    number: 50-99       Set year, (adds 1900 to number)

    number: 1900-2999   Set year

    MON        \\        Day of the week.  Used to select a date at, before, or
    TUE        |        after another date based on what day of the week it
    WED        |        falls on.
    THU        |        e.g.    sunday
    FRI        |                next sunday
    SAT        |                last sunday
    SUN        /                third monday            
                                second last monday        
                                first monday in january                                    

                        Using a day name without any modifier defaults to that
                        day in the current week.  (The current week is defined
                        as Monday to Sunday).


    WEEKDAY             Same as above, but matches any day from Monday to
                        Friday.

    TODAY               Today's date.
    TOMORROW            Tomorrow's date.
    YESTERDAY           Yesterday's date.

    FIRST
    SECOND
    THIRD
    FOURTH
    FIFTH
    SIXTH
    SEVENTH
    EIGHTH
    NINTH               Order modifier, affects how other keywords are used.
                        e.g.      second friday in january

    NEXT                Order modifier, affects how other keywords are used.
                        e.g.    next month
                                next year
                                next sunday
                                
    LAST                Order modifier, affects how other keywords are used.
                        Note that it can also accept FIRST-NINTH modifier to
                        affect it:
                        e.g.      last month
                                  last monday
                                  second last monday in june
                                  last year
                                  first friday last july

    THIS                Order modifier, used with MONTH and YEAR keyword to
                        specific current month or year.

    AFTER               Parses remainder of string, returns full date number
                        plus one.
                        e.g.      second monday after 12 jan                        

    FROM                Parses remainder of string, returns full date number.
                        e.g.      second monday from 12 jan                        

    BEFORE              Parses remainder of string, returns full date number.
                        e.g.      second monday before 12 jan                        

    IN                  Parses remainder of string, returns month/year, or full
                        date number.
                        e.g.      third monday in december 1994

    DAY                 Used with order modifier to select a day.
                        e.g.    last day next month

    MONTH               Used with order modifiers to select a month.
                        e.g.      last month, this month, next month

    YEAR                Used with order modifiers to select a year.
                        e.g.      last year, this year, next year


@{b}@{u}Paste Date Requester:@{ub}@{uu}

The Paste Date requester allows you to enter a day string by clicking on
gadgets instead of typing the date string from the keyboard.  It also
shows you what the date string will result in based on today's date.

It has buttons for all numbers, day names, weekday, month names, first
to 7th, next, last, this, after, before, in, from, day, month, year and
today.

The requester is called from Date string gadgets when clicking on the [?]
gadget  (e.g. the Fill Dates requester).  Also when editing a cell or a
formula, the Paste Date String menu (Amiga-D) brings up the requester and
pastes the selected date string into the cell text.
@endnode
